</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm1.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=986.topic&index=7>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: Mars Direct</span><hr size=1> I think we should commend Zubrin on speaking out. The truth may very well lie somewhere inbetween the two but without strong counter-argument the readers are going to assume the story is totally correct and believe space travel simply too dangerous. Maybe Zubrin has over stated the safety just as the paper over stated the threat but so what. With limited actual data available to form a definite conclusion it's excellent we have someone like Zubrin in our corner. In the legal system &quot;truth&quot; matters for very little. Its all perceptions and deals. The rest of life is very much the same. The truth comes second to public perceptions. Any fearmongering should be stamped out the moment it appears. Allowing such negative sensationalism to grow will break the wheels of this Mars bandwagon. It will then be abandoned on the roadside just like the last one.   <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#333333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=gcnrevenger>GCNRevenger</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Space Lurker</span><br>  Posts: 8<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(1/25/04 10:12 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm1.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=986.topic&index=8>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Mars Bob Strikes Out</span><hr size=1> Of all the places to knock nuclear propulsion...<br>
<br>
I am pretty well versed in what MarsDirect can and can't do, and I agree that MarsDirect probably could get people to Mars and back, but I disagree that it can do any more than this because it is slow, it is small, and it is not safe. If it seems like I am belittling MarsDirect by claiming that it doesn't get much done and cannot be scaled up, that would be because it <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>doesn't</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> get much done <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>nor</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> can it be scaled up. I am also puzzled where you get this nonsense that MarsDirect is somehow “large scale.”<br>
<br>
Now about the payload: <br>
<br>
I really don’t know where you came up with this 80 tons of equipment figure, which would require two additional cargo flight beyond what MarsDirect calls for; maybe you mean the total mass all hardware? Recall that this 40 ton figure <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>includes</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> the mass of the heat shield, retro rockets, and all consumables; I think a figure of around 20-25 tons is more reasonable for actual payload mass. With 6-8 tons and 3-5 tons of this being liquid hydrogen and reactor on the ERV, several more tons for drill rig and rover, and don’t forget the food and consumables - MarsDirect gets small. <!--EZCODE UNDERLINE START--><span style="text-decoration:underline">Fast.</span><!--EZCODE UNDERLINE END--> 40 tons of actual stuff per mission, a reasonable figure I think, may seem like quite a bit, but it is not if you want to do more than get there and back. MarsDirect leaves nothing on Mars but a reactor that is halfway through its life, the cramped HAB module, and a few tons of miscellaneous science gear. <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>Would you please point out the Mars colony payload in this picture?</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> To make matters even worse, the MarsDirect mass estimates are probably a bit optimistic and leave little room for the dreaded weight creep. The basic architecture is possible, but I have doubts you could even afford the pressurized rover and loads of other gear.<br>
<br>
Without that rover, landing site margins of error vanish and the trip becomes markedly more dangerous if you can’t reach the ERV; without equipment like a drilling rig, you might as well not go at all. Even if it was possible to include the rover, building a permanent Mars base of any size a HAB module at a time is ludicrous, even if it were a TransHab. Until Mars mission planners aren’t so bounded by mass limits that they “have to cut the toothbrush handles off” as with MarsDirect no Mars base of any size will take shape, much less a great deal of science done. For comparison, the amount of mass sent per-year is also not very great relative to even maintaining the ISS and its crew of three with something to do, much less an expanding Mars base. A different method to get cargo to and from Mars is required before we can have anything more than a “Martian McMurdro.”<br>
<br>
And about what you intend to do down in the Red,<br>
<br>
Sending a measly four people every two years is not sufficient to even hunt for bugs, much less get any construction done to prepare the way for more. If ISS is any indication, and it doesn’t have to contend with micro-fine dust and heavy use, any Mars mission will require one or two full-time janitors, limiting the hunt for anything to just two or three people, clearly just not enough. A larger crew is a must, cannot be supported by the MarsDirect architecture. Since MarsDirect or any chemically powered ship must use the lowest energy transits to and from Mars and with the limited rate Nasa could build vehicles, this precludes more regular flights which will prevent simply sending more MD missions. The Ares-style SDV is the largest practical chemical rocket to build, and adding bigger tanks or sending up a boost TMI stage won't work very well since the mass ratio would get out of control: a “jumbo” MarsDirect is also a non-starter. <br>
<br>
A six month flight in any event is hazardous to a crew physically and mentally that you expect to do useful work in a lethal environment afterwards. The method MarsDirect uses to &quot;bend&quot; this problem is artificial gravity by spinning on a cable, which adds mass and more failure modes. Spinning also presents issues of communications, solar power, navigation, and conditioning astronauts to walk under the Coriolis force; a bad idea. This also precludes modifying MarsDirect to use an ion engine to improve mass ratios. A shorter flight time will be necessary to make the trip regularly and safely, which reduces the radiation dose too. The dose received by a years’ travel in space will cause around a 1% chance of cancer; not too bad for small missions, but even a fraction of this is fatal for anything larger. Adding shielding adds weight, which MarsDirect cannot tolerate.<br>
<br>
Adding a NERVA-style NTR engine to MarsDirect’s TMI stage does not solve the problem of a 6-month return leg in the ERV, since the NTR engine must use liquid hydrogen which is <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>not</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> produced by Zubrin's fuel factory, oh yes and requires larger fuel tanks. It gets better... even if it were possible to make a chemically power rocket faster without becoming an SEI-sized monster, aerobraking becomes harder and harder the faster you approach, which is plenty dangerous enough as it is. If you wish to point to the MER rovers and their landings, keep in mind that they are a measly few hundred pounds, not 40 tons, which is a world of difference in inertia limits and accuracy requirements. MER Opportunity was subjected to almost 7Gs of force during decent, a lot for humans (or delicate equipment) who have to land a spaceship in the following minute, and the rover only weighed a few hundred pounds.<br>
<br>
And here I thought the idea of getting to Mars was to stay, not for a grand total of <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>the exploring power of two or three whole astronauts</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> to dig for bugs with hand tools.<br>
<br>
This situation is not likely to improve, either. Even with the use of a NERVA-NTR engine, which will make aerobraking more dangerous and not get <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>back</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> any faster, the mass fraction increases only ~30% considering the extra mass of the engine and tanks, and an ion drive won’t work on a spinning rocket. So, <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>the only way to solve the problem of how to get more people and more mass to Mars more often is to abandon MarsDirect.</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END--> <br>
<br>
Economics,<br>
<br>
One of the big issues with MarsDirect is that is entirely expendable. There is no hardware reused other than maybe a HAB module and some bits of science gear, everything else is wasted on every flight. The cost of getting a mere 25 tons of cargo all the way to Mars will also be pretty astronomical, likely around $400-500M when you count launcher development and lander/heat shield, and preclude anything beyond small science missions, which is all that can be managed with MarsDirect. With a orbit-to-orbit ship you can use it over and over again, decreasing how much trouble it is to get there. I am also not real sure where you get the idea that space industry will suddenly blossom to life and buy these expensive launchers when there is so little to do in space without a method of <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>returning</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> large masses to Earth. No no, private industry won’t subsidize space travel beyond the current scale.<br>
<br>
The Nuclear Solution<br>
<br>
The problem with the Bush-I SEI battlestar galactica was a simple mass fraction problem: as many know, to move the next increment of payload you need more fuel, but that fuel has to be pushed by more fuel and so on, so the weight of the rocket grows exponentially. So, you either must make your rocket lighter and do less (MarsDirect), or improve the efficiency of the engine. As mentioned before, NERVA-NTR is not a huge improvement, ion engines don’t have enough thrust for manned flight, and the VASIMR engine will require reactor and magnet technology that is pretty far out there. This leaves GCNR or the ORION system; Orion for all its magnificence is not likely to fly for political reasons (<!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>did you just say you wanted to launch a nuclear howitzer!?</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->), so that leaves GCNR. A gas-core nuclear rocket, which is not far outside the realm of current technology with our advanced fluid dynamics computer modeling and high temperature materials is the only practical, politically acceptable way to go to Mars <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>for keeps.</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> The GCNR ship, which will not be the massive SEI battleship because it needs an order of magnitude less fuel, is not so far away that we ought to waste our time and money on building MarsDirect, which cannot be adapted to use the GCNR effectively. In order to avoid the huge expense of high-order orbital assembly, the Mars ship should be launched in large sections on a HLV like Aries in as few a launches as practical, none of this 30 twenty-ton launches nonsense.<br>
<br>
Be patient fellow spacefarers, don’t be consumed with haste that the promise of space is delayed, wait for the rocket of tomorrow.<br>
